[7/9/2023 9:42 PM] sskarz
This is from what I remember from some years ago
The setting was a mystical place where people could harness the powers of the planets, as the universe revolved around their world, their lives were destined to revolve space and the universe around them. There were colonies of different planets like Mercury, Earth, Saturn, etc. that all had different ideologies about how the world functions. Many of the conflicts in that society occurred because of conflicting ideas between colonies, and would result in turmoil for both sides. So, an order was formed, The Planetary Order, which harnessed the power of the Sun, and there were only 5 individuals that could wield this power. They were exceptional, right from birth, seen as gods and as the absolute right. Anyone that dared to oppose them were considered outcasts, never to be taken seriously, and always viewed as a threat. 

The story revolved around a man that was falsely accused (this was not known yet in the beginning) of violating the Planetary Order (basically the government), of supposedly murdering a family from the Mars Colony. This man was completely innocent, but was framed by someone else seeing him at the crime scene. He was brought upon the Planetary Order's Court, and deemed sentence to death to eternity. It seemed that this man's fate was sealed, that there was nothing he could possibly do to escape from the chains that binded him to the Court's ground. As the guillotine came down, an explosion happened, the court was attacked by a mysterious group of people. See, there weren't just the planets in the solar system that could give powers, and it wasn't a star either, rather the space that fills the rest of the distance between planets and stars and galaxies. The Void itself, which was infamous for denying government power and always seeked righteousness in the free will. The man is then taken by The Void, and together with that group of people, he seeks to take revenge upon the Planetory Order, and seek the man that framed him.


[7/9/2023 9:42 PM] sskarz
sorry if its a bit long, this is just the synopsis of what the story is about

It's the same thing, no one is going to expect you to know the entire class course work and be able to pass calc 1 in a week. And that's okay!!!! It's okay to not know everything right from the beginning. That doesn't mean you're going to fall behind at all. Even if you knew everything, would it seriously change anything? The nervousness, the stress, the feeling of not being able to perform under pressure of work and time management is all still going to be there. And it seems scary, you know I just listed all of those things and I probably made you feel even worse. But believe me when I say, you're not expected to know everything. I know you well enough to say that you won't just be more than fine, but you're going to excel. You're going to be the best person in that classroom, in that subject, and everyone will see you as the smart kid in class! You are nothing short of incredible potential, you've proved it to not just me, but everyone.
Don't let your fears taunt or control you, remember you are either your biggest ally, or the worst enemy. And what changes from an enemy to ally, is a change of perspective. 
So take this change of perspective, the perspective of being okay with going into something knowing nothing, but knowing that you will know more each day to conquer the next challenge.

[8/22/2023 10:05 PM] sskarz

[8/22/2023 10:14 PM] sskarz
If I could say it in one word. I'd say Perspective.
I used to be so overly negative. I hated how I looked, how I acted, how I did things, how I thought. During my middle school years, I fell into a depressive hole and it caused me to set my entire life on fire. There were times where I contemplated running away from everything and everyone, and doing worse things. For a few years, I loathed every day. The friends I talked to I couldn't care less about, the things I did and said held no weight. I was just so... like I felt as if everything was just so much higher and I felt like it was impossible to climb out of that hole yk? When you feel like you're so low, that the bottom floor is closer than getting out, so you just sink. This carried with me all the way into high school, till about Junior year of high school. I started to realize what I was doing to myself and how it also impacted those around me. It wasn't enough to fully make me realize, but it made me change slowly. Of course I couldn't share these feelings with anyone, I kept it all to myself and put on a fake smile for years on end. And then high school ended, and my life took a turn. My perspective just changed, like I just had to snap out of it. And ever since then, I've changed my entire character, my entire person, and my entire perspective of how I view life and people and family and friends and loved ones. It sounds crazy, and honestly, I haven't reflected this hard in a while, but it's true. You wouldn't have liked me if you knew who I was back then. How can you like someone that didn't like themselves.


[8/22/2023 10:16 PM] sskarz
Thankfully, I'm nowhere even close to who I used to be. I'm so much happier being who I am today, than I would ever have been.


[8/22/2023 10:16 PM] sskarz
I love myself to the upmost degree, and my self esteem has never ever been higher


[8/22/2023 10:17 PM] sskarz
Even when I make mistakes today, I just think about the shit I've already gone and done, and it all seems so miniscule. Like nothing could compare to what those years did


[8/22/2023 10:17 PM] sskarz
I know I'm really putting myself out there, and you know maybe this isn't what you wanted to hear


[8/22/2023 10:17 PM] sskarz
but I want to be honest


[8/22/2023 10:18 PM] sskarz
This is who I was, this is who I am today. And this is just me, all of it


[8/22/2023 10:18 PM] sskarz
It's why I preach so much about optimism and perspective, because that's what got me out of all of that. Without that, I wouldn't be who I am today, not even close


[8/22/2023 10:21 PM] prabipyakurel
First of all thank you for sharing, it takes a lot to reflect on the time that has passed. And I am so sorry that you had to go through so much but you got out of it and now you are doing your best. And one thing you gotta remember is to love yourself always, I mean you always here from others but from how much I know you, you are like so amazing. And yea you might have felt like you wanted to be someone else, look different, and maybe see things differently, but you got through those things on your own and it already tells me how strong of a person you are. Thank you for sharing again, I will keep this to myself dw, I am not telling anyone. And your smile is precious, keep it on.

So much so that there were 5 identical fridges, and I checked in each of them and they were all the same. I know, but it gets weirder. As I checked the last fridge, I heard a random ass noise. Now I hadn't heard anything till then, and so I looked at the fridge with a closer eye and noticed there was like a small dog in a cage at the bottom of the freezer in the fridge. So I picked up the dog in the cage and I was like wtf, so I went to go back to where I came from, and for some reason there's just a bunch of the same dogs, but not in cages, all in a pile. And they all just stared at me, and the one I had started growling at me, so I threw it at the other dogs and ran for my life to the door where I came from. And then a dog got on my leg and started biting me and wouldn't let go, but I punted it and then I shut the door behind me. I just kept running and then I woke up
